         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">28/5/91. ¶  ¶ Regret the oversight, dear Prof Watson, in not sending you a complete impression of the "second Census of Austr. plants". ¶  This is now done by the mail. The printing fund was insuffici...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">91.05.28</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Sereno Watson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Gray Herbarium Archives, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">28/5/91.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Regret the oversight, dear Prof Watson, in not sending you a complete impression of the "second Census of Austr. plants".<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B89.12.03.</p>
               </note> This is now done by the mail. The printing fund was insufficient, to furnish a preface and addenda; but a supplement is likely to appear at the end of this year.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">No supplements to the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Second census </seg>are known to have been published.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I do not altogether concur in your views of changes in systems and in names of plants.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M is <seg style="">presumably reacting to the arrangement used in Gray (1890), edited by Watson &amp; Coulter; see pp. 3-18.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> The subject is too large to discuss it in a letter. You may have read however my treatise thereon, written 2 or 3 years ago for the transact. of the R.S. of N.S.W.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B89.05.04.</p>
               </note> also the preface to the first Census.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B83.03.04.</p>
               </note> I may however give some few instances, to illustrate my own ideas.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Two European Professors sent me 2 species of <name key="Polycarpaea">Polycarpaea</name> as <name key="Gomphrena">Gomphrena</name>s, and yet the <name key="Amaranthaceae">Amaranthaceae</name> ar<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">are.</p>
               </note> kept near one end of the system and the <name key="Caryophylleae">Caryophylleae</name> on the other. If RBr overlooked <name key="Wilkia">Wilkia</name> of Scopoli,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Scopoli (1777), p. 317, as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Wilckia</seg>.</p>
               </note> who quotes a specific name! when establishing <name key="Malcolmia">Malcolmia</name>, it was a want of care, particularly at that time, when bot. libraries were not large; if what is not likely<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">What is not likely </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">interlined.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> he willingly passed Scopoli's genus, it was a grave injustice.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Malcolmia">Malcolmia</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="">is recorded in IPNI as being erected by W. T. Aiton (1810-13), vol. 4, p. 121; M lists Brown as the author in B69.07.04, p. 18. The genus is included in the part of the work in which TL2 attributes 'most of the new descriptions' to Brown; the formal authority for these species is given to Aiton as there is no explicit evidence in the protologues that Brown was the author. See Mabberly (1885), p. 186.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Genera with named species like <name key="Hybanthus">Hybanthus</name>, <name key="Bramia">Bramia</name>, <name key="Bladhia">Bladhia</name>, <name key="Temeda">Temeda</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Themeda?</p>
               </note> &amp;c. were simply missed, and not intentionally passed. If such well established genera are left unattended to, where are the exceptions to commence and where to end? <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Fixity of dual names can only be attained</hi>
               </seg> by adopting in all cases the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">first binary name within a correct genus</hi>
               </seg>!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With regardful remembrance your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I hope the woodspecimens for the excellent Prof. Goodale adressed to you, have safely arrived.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Sentence is written in the central and left margins of the sheet comprising pages 2 and 3.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
